const AREAS_EXTRA = {
  property: { id:"property", icon:"", title:"Property Division", slug:"/austin-property-division-lawyer", kw:"property division divorce texas", vol:"400-600/mo", desc:"Community vs. separate property, tracing, reimbursement claims",
    hero:"Austin Property Division Lawyer", heroSub:"Protecting Your Assets in Texas Divorce",
    intro:"Texas community property law is more complex than 'split everything 50/50.' Eric M. Willie ensures your assets — home, retirement, investments, businesses — are properly characterized, valued, and divided.",
    sections:[
      { t:"Community vs. Separate Property in Texas", p:[
        "Texas is one of nine community property states. Everything acquired during the marriage is presumed community property and subject to division. But the division is 'just and right' — not necessarily equal. The court has broad discretion to divide community property 60/40, 55/45, or any ratio deemed fair based on the circumstances.",
        "Separate property includes assets owned before marriage, inheritances received by one spouse during the marriage (even if deposited into a joint account), and gifts made specifically to one spouse. The burden of proving separate property falls on the spouse claiming it, requiring clear documentation and often forensic tracing through years of financial records.",
        "Commingling — when separate and community property are mixed together — creates the most complex tracing challenges. If you deposited a $200,000 inheritance into a joint account used for mortgage payments, groceries, and vacations over 10 years, proving what remains as separate property requires expert forensic analysis. Eric works with forensic accountants who specialize in tracing commingled assets in Texas divorce.",
      ]},
      { t:"The 'Just and Right' Division Standard", p:[
        "Texas courts do not automatically split assets 50/50. Judges consider: fault in the breakup of the marriage (adultery, cruelty); disparity in earning capacity between spouses; which parent has primary custody of the children; each spouse's health, age, and physical condition; education, employment skills, and future employability; the size of each spouse's separate estate; and expected future inheritances or income streams.",
        "This means property division is inherently negotiable. A spouse who was the primary caregiver with limited earning potential may receive a larger share. A spouse whose adultery caused the divorce may receive less. Eric advocates aggressively for the most favorable division based on the specific facts of your case. See our divorce page for more on the overall process.",
      ]},
      { t:"Common Assets and How They're Divided", p:[
        "The Family Home: Usually the largest single asset. Options include selling and splitting proceeds, one spouse buying out the other's interest, or exclusive possession for the custodial parent until the children reach 18. Tax implications differ for each option.",
        "Retirement Accounts: Community portions of 401(k)s, IRAs, pensions, and military retirement are divisible. A Qualified Domestic Relations Order (QDRO) is required to divide most accounts without triggering tax penalties. The division date and account type affect the calculation.",
        "Vehicles, Bank Accounts, and Personal Property: Divided by agreement or court order. Cars are typically kept by the spouse who drives them, with the community equity offset elsewhere. Joint bank accounts are often divided proportionally.",
        "Business Interests: Valued by certified experts and the community interest is divided through buyout, asset offset, or structured payments. See our high net worth divorce page for details on business valuation.",
      ]},
      { t:"Reimbursement Claims in Texas Property Division", p:[
        "Reimbursement claims arise when one estate (community or separate) contributes to another estate's benefit. Examples: community funds used to pay down a separate property mortgage; community funds used to improve a separate property home; one spouse's separate funds used to pay community debts. The amount of reimbursement is the contribution made, not the increase in value. Eric identifies and quantifies reimbursement claims for every client.",
      ]},
      { t:"Debt Division in Austin Divorce", p:[
        "Community debts are divided alongside community assets. Mortgages, car loans, credit cards used for family expenses, and business debts incurred during the marriage are generally community obligations. Debts incurred by one spouse for non-family purposes (gambling, secret credit cards) may be allocated to that spouse alone.",
        "Student loans taken during marriage are often contested. Texas courts consider whether the education benefited the community (higher earning potential) when deciding allocation. Credit card debt in only one spouse's name can still be community debt if used for family expenses.",
      ]},
    ,
      { t:"Hidden Assets in Austin Divorce", p:[
        "Spouses hide assets more often than people expect. Common methods include transferring assets to family members, creating fictitious debts, overpaying the IRS (to receive a refund after divorce), deferring bonuses or commissions, underreporting business income, purchasing expensive items that are easy to undervalue, and opening accounts in other states or countries.",
        "Red flags include: sudden changes in financial behavior, missing financial statements, a lifestyle that does not match reported income, new LLCs or trusts, and large cash withdrawals. Eric works with forensic accountants who use bank deposit analysis, lifestyle analysis, and public records searches to uncover hidden assets. Texas courts can award a disproportionate property division when one spouse conceals assets.",
      ]},
      { t:"The Family Home in Austin Divorce", p:[
        "The family home is usually the largest single asset and the most emotionally charged. Options include: sell the home and split the proceeds — cleanest approach, provides both parties with liquid assets for a fresh start. One spouse buys out the other — requires refinancing the mortgage in one name and paying the other spouse their equity share. Deferred sale — the custodial parent remains in the home until the youngest child turns 18, then the home is sold.",
        "Each option has different tax, financial, and practical implications. Austin\'s real estate market means home equity can represent hundreds of thousands of dollars. Eric works with appraisers and financial advisors to determine the best approach for your situation and ensure accurate valuation.",
      ]}
    ],
    faqs:[
      { q:"Is everything split 50/50 in a Texas divorce?", a:"No. Texas divides community property 'just and right,' which can be unequal based on fault, earning capacity, custody, health, and other factors. Separate property is not divided at all." },
      { q:"What happens to the house in divorce?", a:"Options include selling and splitting proceeds, one spouse buying out the other, or exclusive possession for the custodial parent. The court considers children's stability and each spouse's ability to maintain the home." },
      { q:"Are retirement accounts divided in divorce?", a:"Community portions of 401(k)s, pensions, and IRAs are divisible through a QDRO. Contributions before marriage and growth on pre-marital balances are separate property." },
      { q:"What if my spouse is hiding assets?", a:"Eric works with forensic accountants to uncover hidden assets through discovery, subpoenas, and financial analysis. Hidden assets discovered during divorce can result in a disproportionate division in your favor." },
      { q:"How is a business divided in divorce?", a:"The community interest is valued by experts (income, market, or asset approach) and divided through buyout or offset. The business itself is not split. Only enterprise goodwill is divisible." },
      { q:"What about debts in divorce?", a:"Community debts are divided alongside community assets. Debts for family purposes are community obligations. Debts incurred by one spouse for non-family purposes may be allocated to that spouse." },
      { q:"What is a reimbursement claim?", a:"A claim for repayment when one estate (community or separate) contributed to another estate. Example: community funds paying a separate property mortgage. The amount is the contribution, not the increase in value." },
      { q:"How much does property division cost in a complex divorce?", a:"Attorney fees for complex property cases: $15,000-$50,000+. Forensic accountants: $10,000-$50,000. Business valuators: $5,000-$25,000. Appraisers: $1,000-$5,000 per property." },
    ,
      { q:"Can I get the house in the divorce?", a:"You can negotiate to keep the house by offsetting your spouse\'s equity with other assets (retirement, savings). If children are involved, the custodial parent has a stronger argument for remaining in the home." },
      { q:"What if my spouse hides assets during divorce?", a:"Eric works with forensic accountants to uncover hidden assets. Texas courts can award a disproportionate property division and impose sanctions when a spouse conceals assets." }
    ],
  },
  spousal: { id:"spousal", icon:"", title:"Spousal Support", slug:"/alimony-lawyer-austin-texas", kw:"alimony lawyer austin, spousal maintenance texas", vol:"300-500/mo",
    hero:"Austin Alimony Lawyer", heroSub:"Navigating Texas Spousal Maintenance Law",
    intro:"Texas is one of the hardest states in which to obtain court-ordered spousal maintenance. Eric knows exactly what it takes to secure — or defend against — an alimony award.",
    sections:[
      { t:"Types of Alimony in Texas", p:[
        "Contractual Alimony is agreed upon by both spouses as part of the divorce settlement. There are no statutory limits on amount or duration — it is whatever the parties negotiate. This is the most common form of spousal support in Texas because court-ordered maintenance is so restricted. Contractual alimony can include specific terms, adjustment triggers, and termination events tailored to your situation.",
        "Court-Ordered Spousal Maintenance is much harder to obtain. Texas strictly limits eligibility to specific circumstances: marriages of 10 or more years where the requesting spouse lacks sufficient property and cannot meet minimum reasonable needs through employment; cases involving family violence conviction or deferred adjudication within 2 years of filing; cases where the requesting spouse or a child has a physical or mental disability requiring care; or cases where the requesting spouse cannot earn sufficient income due to incapacitating disability.",
        "Temporary Spousal Support may be ordered while the divorce is pending. This maintains the financial status quo during the case and can include provisions for living expenses, health insurance continuation, and attorney fees. Temporary support ends when the divorce is finalized.",
      ]},
      { t:"Alimony Caps and Duration Limits in Texas", p:[
        "For court-ordered maintenance, Texas imposes strict caps. The amount is limited to $5,000 per month OR 20% of the paying spouse's average monthly gross income — whichever is less. Duration depends on how long the marriage lasted: Marriage of 10-20 years — maintenance for up to 5 years. Marriage of 20-30 years — up to 7 years. Marriage of 30+ years — up to 10 years.",
        "The receiving spouse has an obligation to seek employment and become self-sufficient. The court reviews maintenance periodically and can reduce or terminate it if the receiving spouse is not making good-faith efforts. Contractual alimony has no statutory caps — it is whatever the parties agree upon, making negotiation the preferred path for meaningful spousal support in Texas.",
      ]},
      { t:"Factors Courts Consider for Alimony in Austin", p:[
        "When evaluating a request for court-ordered maintenance, Travis County judges consider: each spouse's financial resources and property; each spouse's education, employment skills, and work history; the length of the marriage; each spouse's age, health, and physical condition; child-rearing responsibilities; marital misconduct (including adultery and cruelty); efforts the requesting spouse has made toward education or job training; and the paying spouse's ability to meet their own needs while paying maintenance.",
      ]},
      { t:"Alimony Tax Implications (Post-2018)", p:[
        "For divorces finalized after December 31, 2018, alimony payments are NOT tax-deductible for the paying spouse and NOT taxable income for the receiving spouse. This is a significant change from prior law and affects the financial analysis of any spousal support arrangement. Both contractual and court-ordered maintenance follow these rules. Eric's analysis accounts for the tax impact when negotiating support terms.",
      ]},
    ,
      { t:"Negotiating Contractual Alimony in Austin", p:[
        "Because court-ordered maintenance is so limited in Texas, the vast majority of meaningful spousal support comes through contractual alimony — negotiated as part of the divorce settlement. Unlike court-ordered maintenance, contractual alimony has no statutory caps on amount or duration. You can negotiate $10,000 per month for 15 years if the other spouse agrees.",
        "Eric uses detailed financial analysis to support alimony negotiations. This includes projecting each spouse\'s post-divorce budget, analyzing career trajectory and earning potential, calculating the standard of living during the marriage, and quantifying the economic impact of career sacrifices made during the marriage (such as a spouse who left the workforce to raise children). Strong financial evidence produces stronger negotiated outcomes. See our property division page for related asset analysis.",
      ]},
      { t:"Spousal Maintenance vs. Contractual Alimony — Key Differences", p:[
        "Court-Ordered Spousal Maintenance: requires eligibility (10+ year marriage or specific circumstances); capped at $5,000 per month or 20% of gross income; limited to 5, 7, or 10 years based on marriage length; modifiable by the court if circumstances change; terminates upon the recipient\'s remarriage or cohabitation.",
        "Contractual Alimony: no eligibility requirements beyond agreement; no caps on amount or duration; terms are whatever the parties negotiate; modifiable only if the agreement allows it; termination events are defined by the contract. Eric drafts contractual alimony agreements with clear terms that protect your interests long-term.",
      ]}
    ,
      { t:"When Alimony Terminates in Texas", p:[
        "Court-ordered spousal maintenance terminates automatically upon: the death of either party; the remarriage of the receiving spouse; the receiving spouse cohabiting with another person in a dating relationship on a continuing, conjugal basis; or the court-ordered end date. The paying spouse can petition to terminate maintenance early if any of these conditions are met.",
        "Contractual alimony terminates according to the terms of the agreement. Eric drafts termination provisions carefully — specifying exact triggering events, notice requirements, and what constitutes \'cohabitation\' to prevent disputes. Without clear definitions, termination disputes can themselves become expensive litigation.",
      ]},
      { t:"How to Prepare for Alimony Negotiations", p:[
        "Whether seeking or defending against alimony, preparation is everything. Gather: three years of tax returns, pay stubs, and W-2s; a detailed monthly budget showing actual expenses; evidence of the marital standard of living; documentation of your education, work history, and earning capacity; medical records if health affects employability; and evidence of contributions to the marriage (homemaking, child-rearing, supporting your spouse\'s career).",
        "Eric builds a detailed financial picture that supports your position. For the requesting spouse, this means demonstrating the gap between your earning capacity and your reasonable needs. For the paying spouse, it means showing your own financial obligations and the requesting spouse\'s ability to become self-supporting.",
      ]}
    ],
    faqs:[
      { q:"Is alimony common in Texas?", a:"Contractual alimony through negotiated settlement is common. Court-ordered maintenance is rare because Texas has strict eligibility requirements and caps at $5,000/month." },
      { q:"How long does alimony last in Texas?", a:"Court-ordered maintenance: up to 5 years for 10-20 year marriages, 7 years for 20-30 year marriages, 10 years for 30+ year marriages. Contractual alimony lasts as long as the parties agree." },
      { q:"Can alimony be modified in Texas?", a:"Court-ordered maintenance can be reduced or terminated if circumstances change (receiving spouse's income increases, paying spouse loses income). Contractual alimony depends on the specific terms of the agreement." },
      { q:"How much alimony will I pay or receive?", a:"Court-ordered maintenance is capped at $5,000/month or 20% of the paying spouse's gross income (whichever is less). Contractual alimony has no cap — it is negotiated." },
      { q:"Does adultery affect alimony in Texas?", a:"The court considers marital misconduct, including adultery, when deciding maintenance. A spouse who committed adultery may be denied maintenance or receive less. Conversely, a faithful spouse may have a stronger claim." },
      { q:"Is alimony tax deductible?", a:"No. For divorces finalized after 2018, alimony is not deductible for the payer and not taxable income for the recipient." },
      { q:"What is the difference between alimony and spousal maintenance?", a:"In Texas, 'spousal maintenance' is court-ordered support with statutory caps and limits. 'Alimony' or 'contractual alimony' is support agreed upon in a settlement with no statutory limits." },
      { q:"How much does an alimony lawyer cost?", a:"Spousal support negotiation as part of divorce: included in overall fees ($10,000-$50,000+ depending on case complexity). Standalone modification: $3,000-$10,000." },
    ,
      { q:"Can I get alimony if my marriage was less than 10 years?", a:"Court-ordered maintenance requires 10+ years unless there was family violence or disability. However, contractual alimony through negotiated settlement has no minimum marriage length — it depends on negotiation leverage." },
      { q:"What if my ex stops paying alimony?", a:"Contractual alimony is enforceable through contempt proceedings. Court-ordered maintenance is also enforceable by the court. Eric files enforcement actions to compel payment." }
    ],
  },
  collaborative: { id:"collaborative", icon:"", title:"Collaborative Divorce", slug:"/austin-collaborative-divorce-lawyer", kw:"collaborative divorce austin, uncontested divorce austin", vol:"200-350/mo",
    hero:"Austin Collaborative Divorce Lawyer", heroSub:"Resolving Divorce Without the Courtroom",
    intro:"Collaborative and uncontested divorce allow couples to reach fair agreements without the expense and conflict of litigation. Lower cost, less conflict, faster resolution, better outcomes for children.",
    sections:[
      { t:"How Collaborative Divorce Works in Austin", p:[
        "In collaborative divorce, each spouse hires a collaboratively trained attorney. Both parties and their attorneys sign a Participation Agreement committing to resolve all issues through negotiation — not litigation. All four people meet together in structured sessions to work through property division, custody, and support.",
        "If the process breaks down and either party files for court, both attorneys must withdraw and the parties start over with new counsel. This creates a powerful incentive for everyone — including the attorneys — to negotiate in good faith and find solutions.",
        "Neutral professionals join the team as needed: a financial neutral (CPA or financial planner) analyzes assets, taxes, and projections; a child specialist assesses the children's needs and recommends parenting plans; and a divorce coach helps each spouse manage emotions and communicate effectively. This multidisciplinary approach addresses the financial, emotional, and parenting aspects of divorce simultaneously.",
      ]},
      { t:"Collaborative Divorce vs. Uncontested Divorce vs. Mediation", p:[
        "These three options are often confused. Uncontested divorce means both spouses agree on ALL terms before filing — no negotiation process is needed, just documentation and court approval. This is the simplest and cheapest path ($3,000-$7,000) but requires both parties to be fully aligned. Collaborative divorce is a structured negotiation process when agreement hasn't been reached yet. Both parties have attorneys. The process costs $10,000-$25,000 per spouse but provides more protection than uncontested filing. Mediation uses a neutral mediator to help resolve disputes. The mediator cannot give legal advice to either side. Each party may or may not have an attorney present. Mediation costs $5,000-$15,000 per spouse.",
        "Eric handles all three approaches and advises which is best for your situation during a free consultation. The right choice depends on the level of agreement, complexity of assets, and the dynamics of your relationship. See our mediation page for more on the mediation process.",
      ]},
      { t:"Benefits of Collaborative Divorce", p:[
        "Cost savings of 40-60% compared to contested litigation. Faster resolution — most collaborative cases settle in 3-6 months versus 12-18 months for contested divorce. Greater control over outcomes — you negotiate the terms rather than having a judge decide. Complete privacy — no public courtroom proceedings, no court records of your financial details. Better co-parenting foundation — the cooperative process models healthy communication for your children.",
      ]},
      { t:"Is Collaborative Divorce Right for Your Situation?", p:[
        "Collaborative divorce works best when both parties are willing to negotiate honestly, both can afford the process, there are no significant power imbalances, and there is no history of domestic violence. It is not appropriate when one spouse is hiding assets, when there is active abuse, or when one party refuses to participate in good faith.",
        "Even if you start with collaboration and it doesn't work, the process often narrows the issues significantly — making any subsequent litigation faster and cheaper.",
      ]},
    ,
      { t:"Uncontested Divorce in Austin, Texas", p:[
        "If you and your spouse already agree on every issue — property division, custody, child support, and spousal support — an uncontested divorce is the fastest and least expensive option. The process involves filing the petition, waiting 60 days, drafting the final decree and settlement agreement, and appearing briefly in court for finalization.",
        "Uncontested divorce in Austin costs $3,000 to $7,000 in attorney fees. Even in uncontested cases, Eric recommends attorney review of the agreement. Issues commonly overlooked include: retirement account division (QDROs), health insurance continuation, life insurance obligations, tax filing status for the year of divorce, and children\'s college expenses. These oversights can cost far more to fix later than an attorney costs upfront.",
      ]},
      { t:"How to Know If Collaborative Divorce Will Work", p:[
        "Collaborative divorce requires both parties to commit to good-faith negotiation. It works best when: both spouses want to minimize the impact on children; both can afford the collaborative process; there are no significant power imbalances; neither spouse is hiding assets or income; there is no history of domestic violence; and both spouses can communicate through their attorneys even when emotions run high.",
        "It is NOT appropriate when: one spouse has a personality disorder that prevents honest negotiation; there is active abuse or intimidation; one spouse is deliberately hiding assets; or the power imbalance is so severe that negotiation cannot be fair. Eric assesses your situation honestly during consultation and recommends the approach most likely to succeed.",
      ]}
    ,
      { t:"The Collaborative Divorce Team in Austin", p:[
        "A full collaborative team includes: each spouse\'s collaboratively trained attorney (who advocate for their client while committed to the cooperative process); a financial neutral — a CPA or certified financial planner who analyzes assets, models settlements, and provides tax projections for both parties; a child specialist — a licensed mental health professional who assesses the children\'s needs, helps develop a parenting plan, and ensures the children\'s voices are heard; and divorce coaches — therapists who help each spouse manage emotions, communicate effectively, and make decisions from a place of clarity rather than anger.",
        "Not every case needs every team member. Simpler cases may only require the two attorneys and a financial neutral. Complex cases with significant parenting issues benefit from the full team. Eric recommends the appropriate team composition based on your specific circumstances.",
      ]}
    ],
    faqs:[
      { q:"What is the difference between collaborative divorce and uncontested divorce?", a:"Uncontested means you already agree on everything — you just need documentation. Collaborative is a structured process to REACH agreement through negotiation with trained attorneys." },
      { q:"How much does collaborative divorce cost in Austin?", a:"Typically $10,000-$25,000 per spouse, which is 40-60% less than contested litigation. Uncontested divorce (already in agreement) costs $3,000-$7,000." },
      { q:"Is collaborative divorce right for me?", a:"It works best when both parties are willing to negotiate honestly. Not appropriate for cases involving domestic violence, hidden assets, or extreme power imbalances." },
      { q:"What if collaborative divorce fails?", a:"Both attorneys withdraw and you start over with new litigation attorneys. This rarely happens because of the mutual investment. Even if it does, the process usually narrows the issues." },
      { q:"How long does collaborative divorce take?", a:"Typically 3-6 months. Uncontested divorce: 60-90 days. Contested litigation: 9-18 months." },
      { q:"Do we need separate lawyers in collaborative divorce?", a:"Yes. Each spouse has their own collaboratively trained attorney who advocates for their interests within the cooperative framework." },
      { q:"Can we use collaborative divorce if we have children?", a:"Yes, and it's often the best option for families with children. The cooperative process models healthy communication and a child specialist can help develop a parenting plan." },
      { q:"What is the difference between collaborative divorce and mediation?", a:"In mediation, a neutral mediator facilitates discussion but cannot give legal advice. In collaborative divorce, each party has their own attorney present throughout the process." },
    ,
      { q:"How much does an uncontested divorce cost in Austin?", a:"$3,000 to $7,000 in attorney fees. Filing fees are approximately $300. This is the most affordable divorce path." },
      { q:"Can we file for uncontested divorce without a lawyer?", a:"Legally yes, but not recommended. Overlooked issues — retirement division, insurance, tax implications — can cost far more to fix later than attorney fees upfront." }
    ],
  },
  adoption: { id:"adoption", icon:"", title:"Adoption", slug:"/austin-adoption-lawyer", kw:"adoption lawyer austin", vol:"200-400/mo",
    hero:"Austin Adoption Lawyer", heroSub:"Building Families Through Legal Excellence",
    intro:"Whether stepparent, agency, private, or interstate — Eric guides families through the adoption process with care, precision, and genuine joy for the family you are building.",
    sections:[
      { t:"Types of Adoption in Texas", p:[
        "Stepparent Adoption: The most common type. A stepparent adopts their spouse's child, creating a full legal parent-child relationship. This typically requires the other biological parent to voluntarily terminate rights or have rights terminated by the court. The process takes 3-6 months in most cases.",
        "Agency Adoption: Working with a licensed adoption agency that matches families with children. The agency handles home studies, background checks, and matching. Agency adoptions can be domestic or international. Domestic agency adoption costs $20,000-$45,000.",
        "Private (Independent) Adoption: The birth mother and adoptive family connect directly or through an attorney, without an agency. Texas requires a post-placement home study. Costs range from $15,000-$35,000.",
        "Interstate Adoption: Adopting a child from another state requires compliance with the Interstate Compact on the Placement of Children (ICPC). Both states must approve the placement before the child can travel.",
        "Adult Adoption: Texas allows adoption of adults for inheritance planning, formalization of family relationships, or other purposes.",
      ]},
      { t:"The Texas Adoption Process Step by Step", p:[
        "Step 1 — Termination of Parental Rights: Before adoption can proceed, the biological parent's rights must be terminated — either voluntarily (signed relinquishment) or involuntarily (court order based on abandonment, neglect, or endangerment).",
        "Step 2 — Home Study: A licensed social worker evaluates the adoptive family's home, finances, background, and parenting capacity. Criminal background checks and CPS records checks are required for all household members over 14.",
        "Step 3 — Placement: The child is placed with the adoptive family. In agency and private adoptions, a waiting period follows before finalization.",
        "Step 4 — Post-Placement Supervision: A social worker visits the home at least twice during the supervision period to assess the child's adjustment and the family's well-being.",
        "Step 5 — Finalization: The court holds a finalization hearing — typically a joyful occasion where the judge formally grants the adoption. The child receives a new birth certificate with the adoptive parents' names.",
      ]},
      { t:"How Much Does Adoption Cost in Austin?", p:[
        "Stepparent adoption: $2,000-$5,000 in attorney fees (if uncontested). Agency adoption: $20,000-$45,000 total. Private adoption: $15,000-$35,000 total. International adoption: $30,000-$60,000+ total. Foster care adoption: minimal cost ($0-$2,500). Adult adoption: $1,500-$3,000.",
        "Many costs include home study fees, background check fees, court filing fees, and legal representation. Eric provides a complete cost breakdown during your initial consultation.",
      ]},
    ,
      { t:"Foster Care Adoption in Texas", p:[
        "Adopting from the Texas foster care system is one of the most rewarding and affordable paths to building a family. There are currently over 10,000 Texas children awaiting permanent homes. Foster care adoption costs are minimal — $0 to $2,500 in most cases, with the state covering many expenses. Training, home studies, and ongoing support are provided free of charge.",
        "The process involves completing PRIDE training (30 hours), passing a home study, being matched with a waiting child, a placement period, and finalization. Eric handles the legal aspects of foster care adoption — termination proceedings if needed, ICPC compliance for interstate placements, and finalization hearings.",
      ]},
      { t:"What to Expect at the Adoption Finalization Hearing", p:[
        "The finalization hearing is one of the most joyful events in family law. The judge formally grants the adoption, the child receives a new birth certificate with the adoptive parents\' names, and the child\'s legal relationship with the adoptive family becomes permanent and irrevocable. Many Travis County judges allow photos and even invite family members to attend.",
        "Eric prepares all finalization documents and attends the hearing with your family. The hearing itself typically takes 15 to 30 minutes. After finalization, the adoptive parents have the same legal rights and responsibilities as biological parents — including inheritance rights, custody rights, and the obligation to support the child.",
      ]}
    ,
      { t:"Birth Parent Rights in Texas Adoption", p:[
        "In Texas, a birth mother cannot sign a voluntary relinquishment of parental rights until at least 48 hours after the child is born. Once signed, the relinquishment becomes irrevocable after the 11th day — giving the birth mother a limited window to change her mind. The birth father\'s rights depend on whether he has established paternity.",
        "If the birth father is known, he must either voluntarily terminate his rights or have them terminated by the court. If the birth father is unknown or cannot be located, the court follows specific notice procedures. Eric navigates these requirements carefully to ensure the adoption is legally sound and permanent. See our paternity page for more on establishing and terminating parental rights.",
      ]},
      { t:"International Adoption Through Austin", p:[
        "International adoption requires compliance with both U.S. federal law and the sending country\'s laws. The Hague Convention on Intercountry Adoption governs adoptions from most countries. The process includes: a home study by a Hague-accredited agency, USCIS Form I-800A approval, matching with a child, and completing the adoption under the foreign country\'s legal system.",
        "Costs range from $30,000 to $60,000 or more. Timelines vary dramatically by country — from 1 to 3 or more years. Eric handles the Texas legal requirements for finalizing international adoptions, including re-adoption proceedings that ensure your child receives a Texas birth certificate and full legal protection.",
      ]}
    ],
    faqs:[
      { q:"How long does adoption take in Texas?", a:"Stepparent (uncontested): 3-6 months. Agency: 6-18 months. Private: 4-12 months. International: 1-3 years. Timeline depends on type, circumstances, and court availability." },
      { q:"How much does adoption cost in Austin?", a:"Stepparent: $2,000-$5,000. Agency: $20,000-$45,000. Private: $15,000-$35,000. Foster care: $0-$2,500. Eric provides detailed cost estimates during consultation." },
      { q:"Can a stepparent adopt without the other parent's consent?", a:"If the other biological parent voluntarily terminates rights, yes. If not, the court can involuntarily terminate rights based on abandonment, failure to support, or endangerment." },
      { q:"What is a home study?", a:"A licensed social worker evaluates your home, finances, background, and parenting capacity. All household members over 14 undergo criminal background checks." },
      { q:"Can single people adopt in Texas?", a:"Yes. Texas law allows single individuals to adopt. The same home study and legal requirements apply." },
      { q:"Can same-sex couples adopt in Texas?", a:"Yes. Same-sex couples have the same adoption rights as opposite-sex couples under federal law. Eric provides affirming representation for all families. See our LGBTQ divorce page for related family law matters." },
      { q:"What is the Interstate Compact (ICPC)?", a:"A legal agreement between states governing the placement of children across state lines. Both states must approve before the child can travel to the adoptive family." },
      { q:"Can I adopt an adult in Texas?", a:"Yes. Adult adoption is available for inheritance planning, formalization of step-family relationships, and other purposes. The process is simpler than minor adoption." },
    ,
      { q:"Can I adopt my partner\'s child?", a:"Yes. Stepparent and second-parent adoption creates a full legal parent-child relationship. This is one of the most common adoption types Eric handles." },
      { q:"How long do I have to wait to adopt?", a:"Stepparent adoption: 3-6 months. Agency: 6-18 months. Foster care: varies widely. Private: 4-12 months. International: 1-3 years." }
    ],
  },
  dv: { id:"dv", icon:"", title:"Domestic Violence & Protective Orders", slug:"/austin-domestic-violence-lawyer", kw:"protective order lawyer austin, domestic violence attorney austin", vol:"300-500/mo",
    hero:"Austin Protective Order Lawyer", heroSub:"Protection When You Need It Most",
    intro:"If you or your children are in danger, Eric can file for emergency protective orders immediately. Safety comes first — every other legal issue can be addressed once you are protected.",
    sections:[
      { t:"How to Get a Protective Order in Austin, Texas", p:[
        "Step 1 — File an Application: You or your attorney files an application for a protective order at the Travis County Courthouse. The application describes the abuse, threats, or harassment you have experienced. Eric prepares and files these applications the same day you contact his office when safety is at risk.",
        "Step 2 — Temporary Ex Parte Order: If the judge finds an immediate danger of family violence, a temporary ex parte protective order is issued the same day — without the abuser being present. This order is effective immediately and lasts up to 20 days until a full hearing.",
        "Step 3 — Full Hearing: Within 14 days, the court holds a hearing where both parties can present evidence. If the judge finds family violence occurred and is likely to occur again, a final protective order is issued lasting up to 2 years.",
        "Step 4 — Enforcement: Violating a protective order is a criminal offense in Texas (Class A misdemeanor, up to 1 year in jail). Repeat violations or violations involving assault can be charged as a third-degree felony.",
      ]},
      { t:"Types of Protective Orders in Texas", p:[
        "Emergency Protective Order (Magistrate's Order): Issued by a judge after a domestic violence arrest, usually at the request of law enforcement. Effective immediately, lasts 31-91 days. No application needed from the victim.",
        "Temporary Ex Parte Protective Order: Filed by the victim or their attorney. Issued without the abuser present if immediate danger exists. Lasts up to 20 days pending a full hearing.",
        "Final Protective Order: Issued after a hearing where both parties present evidence. Lasts up to 2 years (can be extended). Prohibits contact, may grant temporary custody, require surrender of firearms, and mandate counseling.",
      ]},
      { t:"What a Protective Order Can Do", p:[
        "A protective order can prohibit the abuser from going to or near the family home, school, or workplace. It can prohibit all direct and indirect contact (phone, text, email, social media, through third parties). It can grant temporary custody of the children to the victim. It can require the abuser to surrender firearms. It can order the abuser to pay child support and provide for medical expenses related to the abuse. It can mandate participation in a battering intervention program.",
      ]},
      { t:"Protective Orders and Custody", p:[
        "A protective order significantly impacts custody proceedings. A finding of family violence creates a presumption that the abuser should NOT be appointed as a joint managing conservator. The court may order supervised visitation only, or in severe cases, deny visitation entirely. Protective orders and custody orders work together to create a comprehensive safety plan for you and your children. See our child custody page.",
      ]},
      { t:"If You Have Been Falsely Accused", p:[
        "False allegations of domestic violence are used as a strategy in some custody disputes. If a protective order has been filed against you based on false claims, Eric provides aggressive defense. Consequences of a protective order include firearm restrictions, criminal record implications, employment effects, and custody limitations. Fighting false allegations early and aggressively is critical.",
      ]},
    ,
      { t:"Evidence to Bring to Your Protective Order Hearing", p:[
        "A protective order hearing requires evidence that family violence has occurred and is likely to occur again. Strong evidence includes: photos of injuries (with dates), text messages and voicemails containing threats, police reports and 911 call records, medical records documenting injuries, witness statements from family, friends, or neighbors, and any prior criminal history of the abuser.",
        "The more documentation you have, the stronger your case. Start preserving evidence immediately — screenshot text messages, save voicemails, photograph injuries, and request copies of any police reports. Eric helps clients organize and present this evidence effectively at the hearing.",
      ]},
      { t:"Safety Planning During the Legal Process", p:[
        "Your safety is the first priority. Before filing a protective order, develop a safety plan: identify a safe location (family, friend, shelter), pack essential documents (ID, passport, children\'s birth certificates, financial records, medications), inform trusted people about the situation, and save emergency contact numbers.",
        "National Domestic Violence Hotline: 1-800-799-7233 (SAFE). SAFE Alliance Austin: (512) 267-7233. These resources provide immediate shelter, safety planning, and counseling. Eric coordinates with these organizations to ensure comprehensive protection — legal, physical, and emotional.",
      ]}
    ,
      { t:"Criminal vs. Civil Protective Orders in Texas", p:[
        "Understanding the difference between criminal and civil protective orders is important. Criminal protective orders are issued as conditions of bail or probation in domestic violence criminal cases — the victim does not need to petition separately. Civil protective orders are filed by the victim in family court and do not require a criminal case. Both carry criminal penalties for violation.",
        "Eric coordinates between criminal and civil proceedings when both are active. If your abuser has been arrested, the criminal case may result in protective conditions — but a separate civil protective order provides broader protection and can address custody, possession of the home, and financial support. Eric advises on the strongest comprehensive protection strategy.",
      ]}
    ],
    faqs:[
      { q:"How do I get a protective order in Austin?", a:"File an application at the Travis County Courthouse. If immediate danger exists, a temporary ex parte order can be issued the same day. Eric prepares and files applications on an emergency basis." },
      { q:"How long does a protective order last in Texas?", a:"Temporary ex parte orders last up to 20 days. Final protective orders last up to 2 years and can be extended." },
      { q:"What happens if they violate the protective order?", a:"Violation is a Class A misdemeanor (up to 1 year jail, $4,000 fine). Repeat violations or violations involving assault can be charged as a felony." },
      { q:"Can a protective order affect custody?", a:"Yes, significantly. A finding of family violence creates a presumption against joint managing conservatorship for the abuser. The court may order supervised visitation or deny it entirely." },
      { q:"What if I'm falsely accused?", a:"Eric provides aggressive defense against false protective order allegations. The consequences are serious — firearm restrictions, criminal implications, custody effects — and fighting false claims early is critical." },
      { q:"Do I need a lawyer for a protective order?", a:"Not legally required, but strongly recommended. An attorney ensures the application is properly prepared, represents you at the hearing, and coordinates with the criminal case if applicable." },
      { q:"What's the difference between a protective order and a restraining order?", a:"In Texas family law, a 'restraining order' is a temporary order preserving the status quo during divorce. A 'protective order' specifically addresses family violence and carries criminal penalties for violation." },
      { q:"Can I get a protective order for dating violence?", a:"Yes. Texas protective orders cover family violence (family members, household members) and dating violence (current or former dating partners)." },
    ,
      { q:"What evidence do I need for a protective order?", a:"Photos of injuries, threatening texts/voicemails, police reports, medical records, witness statements. The more documentation, the stronger the case. Start preserving evidence immediately." },
      { q:"Can I get a protective order for emotional abuse?", a:"Texas protective orders require \'family violence\' which includes threats of imminent physical harm. Emotional abuse alone may not meet the standard, but threats and intimidation do. Eric evaluates your specific situation." }
    ],
  },
  paternity: { id:"paternity", icon:"", title:"Paternity & Father's Rights", slug:"/austin-paternity-lawyer", kw:"paternity lawyer austin, fathers rights attorney austin", vol:"200-300/mo",
    hero:"Austin Paternity & Father's Rights Lawyer", heroSub:"Establishing and Protecting Parental Rights",
    intro:"Whether you need to establish paternity, assert your rights as a father, or challenge a paternity claim — Eric provides strategic representation that protects your relationship with your child.",
    sections:[
      { t:"Establishing Paternity in Texas", p:[
        "When parents are not married, the father has no legal rights to the child until paternity is formally established. A birth certificate alone does not establish paternity — it must be established through one of three methods:",
        "Acknowledgment of Paternity (AOP): Both parents sign a voluntary acknowledgment form, typically at the hospital after birth. This can be signed later at the Texas Vital Statistics office. The AOP gives the father legal parentage and allows his name on the birth certificate.",
        "Marriage Presumption: If the parents were married at the time of birth, the husband is presumed to be the father. This presumption can be challenged through DNA testing if there is a question of biological parentage.",
        "Court-Ordered Paternity: When paternity is disputed, either parent can petition the court for a determination. The court orders DNA testing (99%+ accuracy) and issues a paternity judgment. Eric handles contested paternity cases in Travis County and surrounding courts.",
      ]},
      { t:"Father's Rights in Austin Custody Cases", p:[
        "Once paternity is established, fathers have EQUAL legal rights to custody and visitation. Texas law does not favor mothers over fathers — the standard is the best interest of the child. Eric has won primary custody for fathers as often as for mothers throughout his career.",
        "However, establishing paternity alone does not automatically grant custody or visitation. The father must separately petition the court for a custody and possession order. Until this order exists, the mother has sole authority over the child. Eric files paternity and custody petitions simultaneously to protect fathers' rights as quickly as possible.",
        "Fathers seeking primary custody should document their involvement: school pickup and dropoff, medical appointments, homework help, meal preparation, bedtime routines, extracurricular activities. This evidence demonstrates active, engaged parenting. Read our blog post 'Fathers Really Do Win Custody' for more on this topic.",
      ]},
      { t:"Challenging Paternity in Texas", p:[
        "If you believe you are not the biological father of a child but are listed on the birth certificate or have been paying support, you can petition to terminate the parent-child relationship. DNA testing can disprove biological connection. However, Texas imposes time limits and considers whether the man held the child out as his own.",
        "Similarly, if you believe you ARE the biological father but another man is listed on the birth certificate (because the mother was married at the time), you can petition to establish your paternity. These cases are time-sensitive — contact an attorney immediately.",
      ]},
    ,
      { t:"Child Support Obligations After Paternity", p:[
        "Once paternity is established, the father has a legal obligation to pay child support. Texas guidelines apply: 20% of net resources for one child, 25% for two, and so on. If the mother has been the primary caregiver, support may be ordered retroactively to the date of the child\'s birth — potentially years of back support.",
        "Fathers who voluntarily pay support without a court order should keep detailed records. Without a court order, voluntary payments may not be credited toward any future support obligation. Eric establishes formal support orders that protect both parents\' rights. See our child support page for detailed information on calculations and enforcement.",
      ]},
      { t:"Putative Father Registry in Texas", p:[
        "The Texas Vital Statistics Unit maintains a Paternity Registry where unmarried men can register as the potential father of a child. Registration must occur before the child is 31 days old. If a man registers and the child is later placed for adoption, the man must receive notice and has the opportunity to assert his parental rights. Failure to register can result in permanent loss of parental rights if the child is adopted.",
      ]}
    ,
      { t:"Father\'s Rights in Unmarried Parent Disputes", p:[
        "Until paternity is formally established, an unmarried father has NO legal rights to custody, visitation, or decision-making for his child — even if his name is on the birth certificate. The birth certificate is not a legal determination of paternity. This means the mother can move with the child, make all medical and educational decisions, and deny the father contact without legal consequence.",
        "Establishing paternity and immediately filing for a custody order is critical. Eric files both petitions simultaneously. Once a court order establishes the father\'s rights, the mother cannot unilaterally deny possession, change schools, or relocate without court approval. Father\'s rights are equal to mother\'s rights under Texas law — but only after they are formally established through the court system.",
      ]}
    ],
    faqs:[
      { q:"How is paternity established in Texas?", a:"Through voluntary Acknowledgment of Paternity (AOP), marriage presumption, or court-ordered DNA testing. Only formal establishment gives the father legal rights." },
      { q:"Do fathers have equal custody rights in Texas?", a:"Yes, once paternity is established. Texas law does not favor mothers. Courts decide custody based on the child's best interest, not the parent's gender." },
      { q:"Can I get custody as an unmarried father?", a:"Yes. First establish paternity, then petition for custody. Eric files both simultaneously to protect your rights as quickly as possible." },
      { q:"Can I challenge paternity in Texas?", a:"Yes. DNA testing can disprove biological paternity. But Texas imposes time limits, so act quickly. Contact Eric immediately if you have concerns." },
      { q:"Does a birth certificate prove paternity?", a:"No. A birth certificate is not a legal determination of paternity. An AOP or court order is required for the father to have legal rights." },
      { q:"What rights do unmarried fathers have?", a:"Until paternity is established, none. After establishment, fathers have equal rights to custody, visitation, and decision-making. A separate court order is needed to exercise these rights." },
      { q:"How much does a paternity case cost?", a:"Uncontested paternity establishment: $2,000-$4,000. Contested paternity with DNA testing: $3,000-$7,000. Paternity plus custody petition: $5,000-$15,000." },
      { q:"Can I request a DNA test?", a:"Yes. Either parent can request court-ordered DNA testing. Modern tests are 99%+ accurate and results are typically available within 1-2 weeks." },
    ,
      { q:"Can I be required to pay back child support after paternity is established?", a:"Yes. Texas courts can order retroactive support to the child\'s birth date. The amount depends on your income during the retroactive period." },
      { q:"What is the Texas Paternity Registry?", a:"A registry where unmarried men can register as potential fathers. Registration within 31 days of birth protects your right to notice if the child is placed for adoption." }
    ],
  },
  grandparent: { id:"grandparent", icon:"", title:"Grandparent Rights", slug:"/austin-grandparent-rights-lawyer", kw:"grandparent rights texas, grandparent visitation austin", vol:"150-250/mo",
    hero:"Austin Grandparent Rights Lawyer", heroSub:"Protecting Your Relationship with Your Grandchildren",
    intro:"Texas law provides limited but important rights for grandparents. Eric helps grandparents establish standing, fight for access, and in extreme cases, seek custody when a parent is unfit.",
    sections:[
      { t:"Grandparent Standing Requirements in Texas", p:[
        "Texas law requires grandparents to establish 'standing' before the court will hear their case. This is the biggest legal hurdle. Under Texas Family Code Section 153.432, a grandparent must prove that denial of possession or access would significantly impair the child's physical health or emotional well-being.",
        "Standing is easier to establish when: the grandparent has had substantial, meaningful past contact with the child; one parent is incarcerated, incompetent, deceased, or has had parental rights terminated; the child has been abused or neglected by a parent; or the child previously lived with the grandparent.",
        "The U.S. Supreme Court's Troxel v. Granville (2000) decision complicates grandparent rights nationwide. The Court held that fit parents have a fundamental right to make decisions about their children's care — including whether to allow grandparent visitation. This means Texas courts give special weight to a fit parent's decision to deny access. Eric understands how to navigate these constitutional standards in Texas courts.",
      ]},
      { t:"Grandparent Visitation vs. Grandparent Custody", p:[
        "Visitation (Possession and Access): Grandparents seek court-ordered time with the grandchild — weekends, holidays, summer visits. This does not affect the parent's custody. The grandparent must prove denial would significantly harm the child.",
        "Custody (Managing Conservatorship): In extreme situations — abuse, neglect, abandonment, substance abuse, incarceration of both parents — grandparents can seek full custody. This requires proving by a preponderance of evidence that the child's present circumstances would significantly impair their physical health or emotional development. This is a higher standard than visitation and requires substantial evidence.",
        "Kinship Care: When CPS removes a child from a parent's home, grandparents are given priority placement consideration. This is different from a custody lawsuit — it's part of the CPS process. Eric helps grandparents navigate both pathways.",
      ]},
      { t:"Building a Strong Grandparent Rights Case", p:[
        "Document your relationship: photos, videos, text messages, school pickup records, birthday celebrations, holiday traditions. The more evidence of a meaningful, ongoing relationship, the stronger your case. Document the parent's unfitness (if seeking custody): police reports, CPS records, criminal history, substance abuse evidence, medical records showing neglect.",
        "Hire an attorney experienced in grandparent rights — these cases involve unique constitutional standards that general family law attorneys may not be familiar with. Eric has handled grandparent rights cases in Travis, Williamson, Hays, and Bastrop county courts.",
      ]},
    ,
      { t:"When CPS Is Involved — Grandparent Kinship Placement", p:[
        "When Child Protective Services removes a child from a parent\'s home, Texas law gives priority to relative placement — including grandparents. If CPS contacts you about taking placement of your grandchild, you have rights and options. Eric helps grandparents navigate the CPS process, understand their obligations as kinship caregivers, and — when appropriate — transition from temporary kinship placement to permanent legal custody.",
        "Kinship caregivers may be eligible for financial assistance, including a monthly stipend, Medicaid for the child, and support services through the Texas Department of Family and Protective Services. Eric ensures grandparents understand all available benefits.",
      ]}
    ,
      { t:"The Emotional Toll and Why Legal Representation Matters", p:[
        "Grandparent rights cases are among the most emotionally difficult in family law. Being denied access to a grandchild is devastating. The legal process — proving that denial harms the child while navigating constitutional standards — requires an attorney who understands both the law and the emotional weight of these cases.",
        "Eric has represented grandparents in Travis, Williamson, Hays, and Bastrop county courts. He understands the local judges, the evidentiary standards, and the most effective strategies. More importantly, he understands what these cases mean to families. Your relationship with your grandchildren is worth fighting for.",
      ]},
      { t:"Grandparent Rights When a Parent Has Died", p:[
        "When a parent dies, grandparents on the deceased parent\'s side often face the surviving parent restricting access to the grandchildren. Texas law provides specific standing for grandparents when one parent has died — the threshold for obtaining visitation may be lower than in cases where both parents are living.",
        "Eric helps bereaved grandparents establish legal visitation rights that preserve the grandchildren\'s connection to their deceased parent\'s family. These cases are time-sensitive — filing promptly after the parent\'s death strengthens the case because the existing relationship is still active and documented.",
      ]}
    ],
    faqs:[
      { q:"Can I sue for visitation with my grandchild in Texas?", a:"Yes, but you must first establish legal standing by proving denial of access would significantly impair the child's well-being. Eric evaluates whether your situation meets Texas requirements." },
      { q:"What if the parents are blocking my access to my grandchild?", a:"If you can show a meaningful prior relationship and that denial significantly harms the child, the court may order visitation over the parents' objection. The constitutional standard requires clear evidence." },
      { q:"Can grandparents get custody in Texas?", a:"In extreme cases involving parental unfitness (abuse, neglect, substance abuse, incarceration of both parents). It requires clear evidence that the child's current situation is harmful." },
      { q:"What is the Troxel v. Granville decision?", a:"A U.S. Supreme Court case establishing that fit parents have a fundamental right to make decisions about their children, including grandparent access. Texas courts give special weight to a fit parent's decision." },
      { q:"How much does a grandparent rights case cost?", a:"Visitation cases: $5,000-$15,000. Custody cases: $10,000-$30,000+. The complexity depends on the parents' position and whether CPS is involved." },
      { q:"Can I get temporary custody through CPS?", a:"If CPS removes a child, grandparents receive priority placement consideration. This is a separate process from filing a custody lawsuit. Eric helps navigate both pathways." },
      { q:"What evidence do I need?", a:"Photos, videos, texts showing your relationship. School records, medical records if you've been involved. For custody: police reports, CPS records, evidence of parental unfitness." },
      { q:"How long does a grandparent rights case take?", a:"Visitation cases: 3-6 months. Custody cases: 6-12 months. Emergency situations may be expedited with temporary orders." },
    ,
      { q:"Can I get paid as a kinship caregiver in Texas?", a:"Yes. DFPS provides monthly kinship payments, Medicaid for the child, and support services. The amount depends on the child\'s needs and the county. Eric helps grandparents access all available benefits." },
      { q:"What if my grandchild is in foster care and I want custody?", a:"Relatives receive priority placement consideration. Contact Eric and CPS immediately to begin the kinship placement process. Time is critical — the longer a child is in foster care, the harder placement changes become." }
    ],
  },
  mediation: { id:"mediation", icon:"", title:"Mediation", slug:"/austin-family-law-mediation", kw:"family law mediation austin", vol:"200-350/mo",
    hero:"Austin Family Law Mediation Lawyer", heroSub:"Resolving Disputes Without the Courtroom",
    intro:"Over 80% of Texas family law cases settle in mediation. Eric has extensive mediation experience as a client advocate — knowing when to push, when to compromise, and when an offer is truly fair.",
    sections:[
      { t:"How Family Law Mediation Works in Austin", p:[
        "Mediation is a structured negotiation facilitated by a neutral third-party mediator. The mediator does not make decisions or take sides — their role is to help both parties find common ground. Each side typically has their own attorney present for advice and advocacy.",
        "In Travis County, mediation is required in most family law cases before the court will set a trial date. Sessions typically last 4-8 hours and are held at the mediator's office. The parties are usually in separate rooms (called 'caucuses') with the mediator shuttling between them. This prevents direct confrontation while allowing negotiation.",
        "If full agreement is reached, the mediator drafts a Mediated Settlement Agreement (MSA). Once signed, an MSA is binding and extremely difficult to set aside — even if you later change your mind. This is why having an experienced attorney present during mediation is critical. Eric ensures you understand every term before signing.",
      ]},
      { t:"What to Expect at Your Mediation Session", p:[
        "Morning (9am-12pm): Opening statements from each attorney summarizing their client's position. The mediator meets with each side separately to understand priorities, concerns, and bottom lines. Initial offers are exchanged.",
        "Afternoon (1pm-5pm): Counteroffers, negotiation, and refinement. The mediator identifies areas of agreement and focuses on resolving remaining disputes. Most progress happens in the afternoon as both sides become more realistic.",
        "If Agreement is Reached: The mediator drafts the MSA. Both parties and their attorneys review and sign it that day. The MSA is filed with the court and incorporated into the final decree.",
        "If No Agreement: The case proceeds to trial. Nothing said in mediation can be used as evidence in court. Partial agreements may be reached on some issues, narrowing what the judge must decide.",
      ]},
      { t:"How to Prepare for Family Law Mediation", p:[
        "Bring: all financial documents (tax returns, bank statements, retirement statements, property appraisals), a proposed parenting schedule if children are involved, a list of priorities (what you must have vs. what you're willing to negotiate), and a realistic understanding of your case's strengths and weaknesses.",
        "Eric prepares clients thoroughly before mediation day. This includes reviewing all financial discovery, calculating support amounts, preparing a property division spreadsheet, and discussing negotiation strategy. Preparation is the difference between a good settlement and a bad one.",
      ]},
      { t:"Benefits of Mediation vs. Trial", p:[
        "Cost: mediation typically costs $3,000-$8,000 per side for the session. Trial costs $15,000-$50,000+ per side. Time: mediation resolves in one day. Trial preparation and the trial itself take months. Control: in mediation, you shape the outcome. At trial, a judge decides. Privacy: mediation is confidential. Trial is public record. Compliance: people are more likely to follow agreements they helped create than orders imposed by a judge.",
      ]},
    ,
      { t:"Choosing a Mediator in Travis County", p:[
        "The choice of mediator matters. Austin has dozens of qualified family law mediators, each with different styles and specialties. Some mediators are evaluative — they tell both sides their opinion of how a judge would rule. Others are facilitative — they help parties find solutions without expressing opinions. Some specialize in high-conflict cases, others in complex property, and others in child-centered mediation.",
        "Eric recommends mediators based on the specific needs of each case. For high-conflict custody disputes, a mediator experienced in high-emotion situations is critical. For complex property cases, a mediator with financial expertise is essential. The mediator\'s fee is typically split between the parties and ranges from $300 to $600 per hour.",
      ]},
      { t:"After Mediation — What Happens Next", p:[
        "If full agreement is reached, the Mediated Settlement Agreement (MSA) is signed by both parties and their attorneys. The MSA is then filed with the court and incorporated into the Final Decree of Divorce. Once signed, an MSA is extremely difficult to set aside — Texas courts will only vacate an MSA if it was procured by fraud, duress, or coercion, or if it is unconscionable.",
        "If mediation is partially successful — agreement on some issues but not all — the agreed terms are memorialized and the remaining issues proceed to trial. This significantly reduces trial time and cost. Even \'failed\' mediations often narrow the disputed issues from many to few.",
      ]}
    ,
      { t:"Common Mediation Mistakes to Avoid", p:[
        "Going in without preparation — not knowing what your assets are worth or what child support guidelines produce. Making emotional decisions — agreeing to terms you\'ll regret because you want the process over. Not understanding tax implications — accepting property that looks equal on paper but is worth less after taxes. Signing the MSA without your attorney reviewing every term. Refusing to negotiate on minor points — being inflexible on small issues can destroy the chance of resolving major ones.",
        "Eric prepares every client to avoid these mistakes. By the day of mediation, you\'ll know your financial picture, your legal options, your best-case and worst-case outcomes, and your strategy for the session. Preparation is the difference between a good settlement and a bad one.",
      ]}
    ],
    faqs:[
      { q:"Is mediation required in Texas family law cases?", a:"In most Travis County cases, yes. Courts typically order mediation before setting a trial date. Exceptions exist for protective order situations." },
      { q:"Can I have my attorney at mediation?", a:"Yes, and you absolutely should. Eric advocates for your interests throughout mediation and ensures any agreement protects your rights before you sign." },
      { q:"What if mediation fails?", a:"The case proceeds to trial. Nothing said in mediation can be used as evidence in court. Partial agreements on some issues may still stand." },
      { q:"How much does family law mediation cost in Austin?", a:"The mediation session itself: $3,000-$8,000 per side (mediator fee split plus attorney time). Total cost for the full process is far less than trial ($15,000-$50,000+)." },
      { q:"What is a Mediated Settlement Agreement (MSA)?", a:"A binding agreement signed at the end of successful mediation. Once signed, an MSA is extremely difficult to set aside. It is incorporated into the final divorce decree." },
      { q:"How long does mediation take?", a:"Most sessions last 4-8 hours in a single day. Complex cases may require a second session. Compare to trial preparation and trial itself, which takes months." },
      { q:"Can mediation work for high-conflict cases?", a:"Often, yes. The separate-room format prevents direct confrontation. The mediator manages communication. Even high-conflict cases frequently settle when both sides face the reality of trial costs and uncertainty." },
      { q:"How do I choose a mediator?", a:"Eric recommends mediators he has worked with based on your case type. Some mediators specialize in high-asset cases, others in custody disputes. The right match matters." },
    ,
      { q:"Can a mediator force us to agree?", a:"No. Mediation is voluntary. The mediator facilitates discussion but cannot impose a decision. Only a judge at trial can make binding decisions over objection." },
      { q:"What if I signed an MSA and changed my mind?", a:"An MSA is binding once signed. It can only be set aside for fraud, duress, or coercion — an extremely high standard. This is why having an attorney present during mediation is essential." }
    ],
  },
  enforcement: { id:"enforcement", icon:"", title:"Enforcement & Modification", slug:"/austin-custody-modification-lawyer", kw:"custody modification lawyer austin, enforcement of court orders austin", vol:"300-450/mo",
    hero:"Austin Custody Modification & Enforcement Lawyer", heroSub:"When Court Orders Need to Change — Or Be Enforced",
    intro:"Life changes. Court orders should reflect your current reality. Whether you need to modify custody, support, or property terms — or enforce an order the other party is violating — Eric fights for compliance and fairness.",
    sections:[
      { t:"Modification of Custody Orders in Texas", p:[
        "Texas allows modification of conservatorship (custody) and possession (visitation) orders when there has been a material and substantial change in circumstances since the last order. Common triggers include: relocation by one parent, remarriage or new partner, changes in the child's needs (medical, educational, behavioral), safety concerns in one home, the child reaching age 12 and expressing a preference, and changes in a parent's work schedule or lifestyle.",
        "For modifications filed within one year of the previous order, the standard is even higher — you must prove the child's present environment may endanger their physical health or significantly impair emotional development. After one year, the standard relaxes to material and substantial change. Eric evaluates your circumstances and advises whether modification is likely to succeed before you invest in filing.",
      ]},
      { t:"Child Support Modification", p:[
        "Child support can be modified when: there is a material and substantial change in circumstances (job loss, significant income change, change in child's needs, new dependents); OR the existing order has been in effect for 3 or more years AND the current amount differs by 20% or $100 from what guidelines would produce today. The 3-year rule means many parents are eligible for modification even without a dramatic life change — income naturally shifts over time. See our child support page for details on how support is calculated.",
      ]},
      { t:"Enforcement of Court Orders in Austin", p:[
        "When the other parent or former spouse violates a court order, enforcement proceedings hold them accountable. Common violations include: failure to pay child support, denying court-ordered possession (visitation), making unilateral decisions about the child's school, residence, or medical care, failure to follow specific provisions of the decree (insurance, property transfers, retirement division), and interfering with the other parent's relationship with the child.",
        "Enforcement remedies include: contempt of court (up to $500 fine and 180 days in county jail PER violation); wage garnishment for unpaid support; suspension of driver's license, professional licenses, and recreational licenses; property liens; passport denial for arrears over $2,500; makeup possession time for denied visitation; and an award of the complaining party's attorney fees. Eric pursues enforcement aggressively.",
      ]},
      { t:"The Enforcement Process Step by Step", p:[
        "Step 1: Eric reviews your current order and the specific violations. Step 2: A Motion for Enforcement is filed with the court, detailing each violation with dates and evidence. Step 3: The violating party is served and given the opportunity to respond. Step 4: An enforcement hearing is held where both sides present evidence. Step 5: If violations are proven, the court issues sanctions — contempt, fines, makeup time, attorney fees.",
        "For child support enforcement, the Texas Attorney General's office provides free enforcement services but handles a massive volume of cases. Hiring a private attorney like Eric typically produces faster and more aggressive results.",
      ]},
    ,
      { t:"Relocation and Geographic Restriction Modification", p:[
        "If your custody order includes a geographic restriction and you need to relocate — for a new job, to be closer to family, or for a fresh start — you must petition the court for modification BEFORE moving with the child. Moving without court approval can result in contempt charges, loss of custody, and an order to return the child immediately.",
        "The court evaluates whether the relocation serves the child\'s best interest. Factors include: the reason for the move, the quality of life in the new location, the impact on the child\'s relationship with the other parent, and the child\'s ties to the current community. Eric prepares detailed relocation cases with evidence supporting each factor. See our child custody page for more on how courts evaluate the best interest standard.",
      ]},
      { t:"Emergency Modification in Austin", p:[
        "In situations involving immediate danger to a child — abuse, neglect, substance abuse in the home, or a parent\'s arrest — the court can issue emergency temporary orders without the standard notice period. These orders take effect immediately and last until a full hearing can be held (typically within 14 days).",
        "Eric files emergency modification petitions when the child\'s safety is at risk. These cases require strong evidence presented quickly. If you believe your child is in danger, call Eric\'s office immediately.",
      ]}
    ,
      { t:"Modifying Spousal Support and Property Terms", p:[
        "Court-ordered spousal maintenance can be modified when circumstances change — the receiving spouse\'s income increases, the paying spouse loses their job, or other material changes occur. Contractual alimony can only be modified if the original agreement allows it.",
        "Property division terms in the final decree are generally NOT modifiable — they are a final division of assets. However, enforcement is available when the other party fails to transfer property, pay a buyout, or comply with other financial terms. Eric pursues enforcement aggressively. Visit our alimony page for detailed information on spousal support modification.",
      ]}
    ],
    faqs:[
      { q:"When can I modify a custody order in Texas?", a:"When there has been a material and substantial change in circumstances since the last order. Common triggers: relocation, remarriage, safety concerns, child's changed needs, child turning 12." },
      { q:"What if my ex won't follow the court order?", a:"File an enforcement motion. Contempt of court can result in fines, jail time, makeup possession, and an award of your attorney fees." },
      { q:"How long does modification take in Austin?", a:"Typically 2-4 months from filing to hearing, depending on the court's docket and complexity. Emergency modifications can be expedited." },
      { q:"Can I modify child support?", a:"Yes — with material change in circumstances, or if the order is 3+ years old and differs by 20% or $100 from current guidelines." },
      { q:"What is contempt of court?", a:"A finding that someone willfully violated a court order. Penalties include up to $500 fine and 180 days in jail per violation. The court can also award the other party's attorney fees." },
      { q:"Can I enforce a property division order?", a:"Yes. If your ex fails to transfer property, pay a buyout, or comply with financial terms of the decree, enforcement proceedings can compel compliance." },
      { q:"How much does a modification or enforcement case cost?", a:"Modification: $3,000-$10,000 depending on complexity. Enforcement: $3,000-$15,000. Cases involving contempt hearings cost more." },
      { q:"Can I modify if I'm moving out of state?", a:"Relocation is a common basis for modification. The court will evaluate whether the move is in the child's best interest and may adjust the possession schedule accordingly." },
    ,
      { q:"Can I move out of state with my child?", a:"Not if your order has a geographic restriction — you must petition for modification first. Moving without court approval can result in contempt and loss of custody." },
      { q:"What is an emergency custody modification?", a:"When a child faces immediate danger, the court can issue temporary orders without standard notice. Evidence of abuse, neglect, or substance abuse in the home is required." }
    ],
  },
};

